defaultCase Study – defaultfemale umpires in the defaultNorthumberland Cricket League defaultIn 2011 
defaultOfficials Gillian Woodley and Sarah Lee have
default become the first two women to take charge of a match in one of the North’s top leagues
default.
default Gillian is a fully qualified umpire having attained her Level Two 
defaultqualification 
defaultlast year. Sarah previously scored for Blyth Second XI and this is her second season um
defaultpiring, after passing her Level One from the English Cricket Board’s Association of Cricket Officials.
defaultGillian, from Gosforth, Newcastle, said: “I admit I once hated the sport but I was becoming a cricket widow because my husband loves it. I had to grow to
default like it just to see him at weekends. 
default 
default 
defaultI started as a scorer and got hooked so I decided to get my qualifications at the same time as Peter. It’s a fascinating sport and I love it now. I think I’ve gained respect from the men players.
default 
default It was difficult at first when I did my first matches four years ago because I think some men found it hard to accept decisions from a woman. 
default 
defaultBut I think now I’ve shown I can do it and it’s something I very much enjoy.
default 
default It would be lovely to see more wom
defaulten doing it. There’s a great team spirit among the umpires, but it’s always nice to see a few women walking out there.”
defaultSarah, from Blyth, Northumberland, is studying A-levels at Newcastle College but spends her weekends 
defaultat cricket matches
default across the county.
