default3.3
default              
defaultCapital Investment into Facilities
defaultThrough the last Sport England funding period the ECB have targeted women’s and girls’ participation through capital investment – identifying where access to facilities are barriers and require investment to increase participation. Over the 4 year period t
defaulthe ECB invested £5.4m to specifically support women and girls cricket. This totalled 57 awards across approximately 26 projects with the majority of these going to our recreational clubs. Supporting this capital investment, first class counties and clubs e
defaultnsured revenue funding was aligned to support growth in women’s cricket. 
defaultInitial statistics have seen increases in participation across the awards with a 72% increase amongst 5 – 15 year olds and 40% increase in participation of 16 – 24 year olds. 
defaultIn add
defaultition to this targeted funding, other revenue and capital investment is made available to support club programmes and the wider network to support women and girls cricket and clubs within England and Wales.
default3.4
default              
defaultProtection of Local Authority and School pitc
defaulthes
defaultIn order for Women and Girls’ participation to continue to grow they must have access to decent local facilities and pitches. 
default 
defaultOver 40% of cricket is played on local authority pitches and Central Government must make sure that local leisure provision i
defaults a key 
defaultcriterion 
defaultby which local authorities are held to account for their spending by the Department for Communities and Local Government. 
default 
defaultAs sport is not a statutory service it too often a soft option for cuts. 
default&#xa0;
defaultECB welcomed the enhanced protections ou
defaulttlined in the Government’s National Planning Policy framework but remains very concerned at the on-going threat to the infrastructure of pitches and facilities available to sports within the local authority framework which is under extreme budgetary pressu
defaultres. 
default 
defaultPlaying fields are also under threat from developers on certain sites such as Civil Service grounds.
default&#xa0;
defaultGreater effort needs to go into provision of pitches and facilities. 
default 
defaultWhether these are maintained by local authorities, volunteer groups or cricket
default clubs on-going support needs to be given to addressing the poor state of pitches and increasing quality standards.
default&#xa0;
defaultRecently all of the major pitch sports have jointly with Sport England, revised the planning model for local authority playing pitch strate
defaultgies.
default 
default Through this model all pitch sports have committed to collaborating and working with Local Authorities on the strategic provision of sport. 
default 
defaultSupply, demand, disposal and quality are all measured through this process.
