default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;defaultThe ECB approach, as documented in 
defaultthis submission, is to create a fully accessible sport at every level of the game to ensure that we continue to grow the sport and make the right interventions to remove as many of the barriers to playing as possible.
defaultThere are many well documented reasons
default for a drop out in sport - physical, environmental and social factors all can play their part to greater or lesser extent and the ECB is keen to understand 
defaultmore and to make sure our programmes adapt and meet the needs and requirements of those women and gi
defaultrls wanting to participate in the sport. In reality it is the same barriers that prevent women playing as men. 
defaultOne of the key interventions a National Governing Body (NGB), such as the ECB, can make is to promote physical literacy at an early age, as part
default of a young person’s personal and emotional development and then in time provide the right opportunities to play competitively. It can provide teachers with the necessary training and coaching support to help young people begin to develop a habit for life.
default In our view it is vital that this development process is driven within the school system, to allow sports such as cricket to create a development journey from childhood to adulthood with different opportunities to play to meet the demand.
defaultAs outlined, the
default ECB through its partnerships has well established programmes at primary school level such 
defaultAsda 
defaultKwik Cricket which has a huge reach offering both mixed and programmes focused specifically on girls. 
